'''Alfred James Wilmott''' (1888<U+2013>1950) was primarily an English botanist and museum curator. His author standard form is Wilmott and his area of interest was [[spermatophyte]]s.<ref>[http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idAuthorSearch.do?id=11727-1&show_history=false&output_format=normal IPNI]</ref> He also [[species description|describe the species]] ''[[Sorbus bristoliensis]]''.<ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:MIbIdXp2Z6AJ:archive.bsbi.org.uk/Wats27p37.pdf+A+J+Wilmott+sorbus&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESg3Fa3U1bo5u1LrD__PMAdaG-KpbDKF0xXxrKZc93n4CMgauUgUe55c-XvVSOHdJqcP0yuyuhdgGVcewQwMXvhMcMQKOKPmrqYauXhZ42ar1RvgGm6XSjeppMPALxnLJqNQSeQn&sig=AHIEtbTVm29928zkuQMsgRVSPHNFSi4GBg Department of Biodiversity and Systematic Biology, National Museum of Wales]</ref> 

His father was an academic who taught at Homerton Training College. Wilmott entered [[St John's College, Cambridge]] and graduated from University in 1910. His mentor was [[Charles Edward Moss]]. Wilmott had an interest in ''[[Salicornia]]'' and did much work for the [[Natural History Museum]]. Although botany and museum work was his career he also played table tennis receiving the title for the [[English Open (table tennis)#Veteran Events|Veteran Singles Champion in 1934-1935]]. In table tennis he also introduced a method for testing table tennis balls.<ref>[http://plants.jstor.org/person/bm000154638 JSTOR Plant Science]</ref><ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:lGRvhDzYKqgJ:www.ittf.com/museum/TTIscans/TTI65Photos.pdf+%22A.+J.+Wilmott%22+tennis&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESirqb92s1Zal4nbJafMsT0sSH3sqCGkB_gTe-cbXpS0gGbWGLyk3nfGoLUoQRkONfiuEFDty4wh03rfhFMWR8aAfESNjNJEGXE-pjutCDm0nSMfJgLDDNEN_thWiFCCJfsJQl_1&sig=AHIEtbS9xgzIhfZc3l2ggsoE-HC7KgDE3Q ITTF]</ref>

